<div style="font-size: inherit;">FR1: Visibility and Accessibility\r\nFR1.1: Prominent Display\r\nThe search bar should be immediately visible to users when they land on any primary page of the website. It should be positioned in a consistent location across pages, such as the header, to ensure easy access.\r\n\r\nFR1.2: Persistent Accessibility\r\nThe search bar should remain accessible even as the user scrolls down the page. It should be designed as a floating element or part of a sticky header that moves with the scroll.\r\n\r\nFR2: Input and Interaction\r\nFR2.1: Text Input\r\nThe search bar must accept alphanumeric input from users. It should respond to both single-character and multi-character inputs, allowing for partial and complete product names or descriptions.\r\n\r\nFR2.2: Keyboard Navigation\r\nUsers should be able to navigate through the autocomplete suggestions and initiate a search using keyboard controls, such as the arrow keys to navigate and Enter to select.\r\n\r\nFR2.3: Clear Input Feature\r\nThere must be a clear button within the search bar that, when clicked, immediately clears any text input by the user, resetting the search bar to its default state.\r\n\r\nFR3: Search Functionality\r\nFR3.1: Search Initiation\r\nThe platform must initiate a search when the user confirms their query, either by pressing the \"Enter\" key or by clicking a search icon adjacent to the search bar.\r\n\r\nFR3.2: Autocomplete Suggestions\r\nThe search bar should provide real-time suggestions to the user as they type, based on popular searches and matching products from the catalog.\r\n\r\nFR3.3: Voice Input\r\nThe platform shall offer the option to use voice commands to input search queries, increasing accessibility and convenience.\r\n\r\nFR4: Search Results\r\nFR4.1: Results Dropdown\r\nA dropdown should appear beneath the search bar as the user types, showing potential matches. This dropdown should be navigable via mouse or keyboard.\r\n\r\nFR4.2: Display of Search Results\r\nThe dropdown will display products with their images, names, and prices in a clear and concise format.\r\n\r\nFR4.3: No Results Message\r\nWhen no products match the query, the search bar should display a polite message such as \"No products found. Please try another search.\"\r\n\r\nFR5: Search Filtering\r\nFR5.1: Filter Options\r\nThe search bar should allow users to filter the search results without leaving or reloading the search page, refining the displayed products according to selected criteria.\r\n\r\nFR5.2: Dynamic Filtering\r\nAs filters are applied, the options available should adjust to reflect the current products being shown in the results.\r\n\r\nFR6: Performance\r\nFR6.1: Search Speed\r\nThe system must return search results quickly, aiming for a response time of two seconds or less after the user initiates a search.\r\n\r\nFR6.2: Concurrent Search Handling\r\nThe search function should be robust, capable of handling a high volume of searches simultaneously without a drop in performance.\r\n\r\nFR7: Security\r\nFR7.1: Code Execution Prevention\r\nThe search bar shall not execute any part of the input as code, preventing potential attacks.\r\n\r\nFR7.2: Input Sanitization\r\nAll inputs shall be sanitized server-side to avoid SQL injection attacks and ensure that special characters are treated as text.\r\n\r\nFR8: Usability\r\nFR8.1: Accessibility Compliance\r\nThe design of the search bar should accommodate users with disabilities, adhering to recognized web accessibility guidelines.\r\n\r\nFR8.2: User Feedback\r\nThe system shall provide immediate visual feedback when a search is in progress, such as a spinner or progress bar.\r\n\r\nFR9: Analytics and Logging\r\nFR9.1: Query Logging\r\nAll searches should be logged anonymously for data analysis, helping to improve the search algorithm and product offerings.\r\n\r\nFR9.2: Privacy Protection\r\nUser privacy must be safeguarded by ensuring that search logs cannot be traced back to specific users.\r\n\r\nFR10: Error Handling\r\nFR10.1: User-Friendly Error Messages\r\nIn the event of a search failure, the system must display an error message that is understandable and provides guidance on what the user can do next.\r\n\r\nFR10.2: Error Logging\r\nErrors encountered during the search process should be logged internally for technical review and debugging purposes.<br></div>
